y sought to do through lectures, journalism, and science education. They devoted enormous effort to the expansion of science education, with real, but mixed, success. ​For twenty years, the X Club was the most powerful network in Victorian science—the men succeeded each other in the presidency of the Royal Society for a dozen years. Barton’s group biography traces the roots of their success and the lasting effects of their championing of science against those who attempted to limit or control it, along the way shedding light on the social organization of science, the interactions of science and the state, and the places of science and scientific men in elite culture in the Victorian era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain. 0aScience clubsxHistoryx19th centuryxEnglandxLondon. 0aScience clubszEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencexHistoryx19th centuryxEngland. 0aSciencezEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acultural authority.  adignity and independence of science.  agroup biography.  aheroic histories.  aimportance of allies.  ainfrastructure for scientific research.  anaturalism.  aprofessionalizers of science.  asecular culture and society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226551753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226551753/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles